07313nam a22008775i 9780226627878DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019002937  a9780226627878  a(DE-B1597)535688  a(OCoLC)1109390543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBM545.D35bM326 2019 4aBM545.D35bM326 2020 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a181.0622300aMaimonides' "Guide of the Perplexed" in Translation :bA History from the Thirteenth Century to the Twentieth /ced. by Yonatan Shemesh, James T. Robinson, Josef Stern. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b14 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. The History of Translations of the Guide -- t1. Moreh ha-nevukhim: The First Hebrew Translation of the Guide of the Perplexed -- t2. Al-Ḥarizi’s Translation of the Guide of the Perplexed in Its Cultural Moment -- t3. Dux neutrorum and the Jewish Tradition of the Guide of the Perplexed -- t4. Pedro de Toledo’s Mostrador e enseñador de los turbados: The Christian Reception of Maimonides’ Guide in Fifteenth-Century Spain -- t5. The Second Ibn Tibbon: Salomon Munk and His Translation of the Guide -- t6. Michael Friedländer’s Pioneering English Translation of the Guide -- t7. The Elegance of Precision: On Pines’s Translation of the Literary Parts of the Guide -- t8. Pines’s Translation of the Guide: Alternative Possibilities -- t9. Rabbi Yosef Qafih’s Modern Medieval Translation of the Guide -- t10. Michael Schwarz’s Hebrew Translation of Maimonides’ Guide of the Perplexed -- t11. Key Terms in Translations of Maimonides’ Guide of the Perplexed -- tPART II. The Impact of the Guide in Translation -- t12. Maimonides and Aquinas on Divine Attributes: The Importance of Avicenna -- t13. The Guide of the Perplexed in Early Modern Philosophy and Spinoza -- t14. Shlomo Pines and the Rediscovery of Maimonides in Contemporary Philosophy -- t15. Maimonides as a Student of Islamic Religious Thought: Revisiting Shlomo Pines’s “Translator’s Introduction” and Its Comments on al-Ghazālī -- tEditions and Translations of the Guide -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoses Maimonides’s Guide of the Perplexed is the greatest philosophical text in the history of Jewish thought and a major work of the Middle Ages. For almost all of its history, however, the Guide has been read and commented upon in translation—in Hebrew, Latin, Spanish, French, English, and other modern languages—rather than in its original Judeo-Arabic. This volume is the first to tell the story of the translations and translators of Maimonides’ Guide and its impact in translation on philosophy from the Middle Ages to the present day. A collection of essays by scholars from a range of disciplines, the book unfolds in two parts. The first traces the history of the translations of the Guide, from medieval to modern renditions. The second surveys its influence in translation on Latin scholastic, early modern, and contemporary Anglo-American philosophy, as well as its impact in translation on current scholarship. Interdisciplinary in approach, this book will be essential reading for philosophers, historians, and religious studies scholars alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJewish philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aMaimonidean tradition.  aconsistency.  aimpact.  aphilosophical vocabulary.  atranslation.  atranslators’ lives.1 aFenton, Paul B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffel, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/